item.title: ICUs on Rails: How France Coped With a Surge of Coronavirus Patients
item.description: French authorities transported patients over hundreds of miles from hot spots to areas less affected by the outbreak, in a model that could be used elsewhere if a second wave of infections arrives

item.title: Latin America, Wary of Exported Coronavirus, Voices Concern Over U.S. Deportations
item.description: Governments in Latin America, already struggling to contain the coronavirus from spreading in their countries, are now contending with a new challenge: importing additional cases of the pathogen from migrants deported by the U.S.

item.title: U.S. Allies Are Slow to Fill WHO Funding Gap as China Steps In
item.description: America’s allies have been reluctant to fill the gap left by the U.S. decision to halt funding for the World Health Organization because of concerns over the agency’s management of the coronavirus pandemic.

item.title: Closed Mosques and Crowd Restrictions Mark a Muslim Holy Month Like No Other
item.description: Countries with large Muslim populations are struggling to balance the risk of a new surge in coronavirus infections against the weight of traditions that involve getting together for food and worship during the holy month of Ramadan.

item.title: Virus-Plagued Brexit Talks Fail to Progress Much
item.description: Brexit trade talks hit early troubles as British and European Union negotiators accused each other of being inflexible.

item.title: Pandemic Deepens Catholic Church's Financial Crunch
item.description: The pandemic has hurt the Catholic Church’s finances, threatening its charitable activities and leading bishops and parish priests to slash expenses and seek funds elsewhere.

item.title: Forgotten Pandemic Offers Contrast to Today's Coronavirus Lockdowns
item.description: Warnings of a potential second wave of coronavirus cases reflect the experience of a relatively recent outbreak—the Hong Kong flu of the late 1960s.
